SEC. 2.

Definition of Terms.

â As used in this Act, the following terms shall mean:

Counting Machine

â a machine that uses optical scanning/mark sense reading device or any similar advanced technology to count ballots;

Memory Pack /Diskette

â a device used to store data;

Memory Pack Receiver

â a dedicated machine that reads memory packs;

Tape Printout

â an adding machine-like tape containing the names of all candidates and the corresponding votes obtained per precinct directly produced by the counting machine;

Election Returns

â a document showing the date of the election, the municipality in which it is held, and other data, and containing the votes in words and in figures for each candidate in a precinct;

Statement of Votes

â a document containing detailed entries of the votes obtained by each candidate in each of the precincts in a municipality or in each of the municipalities in a province;

Municipal Certificate of Canvass of Votes

â a document containing the total votes in words and in figures obtained by each candidate in a municipality;

Provincial Certificate of Canvass of Votes

Provincial Certificate of Canvass of Votes

â a document containing the total votes in words and in figures obtained by each candidate in a province;

Computer Set

â a set of equipment containing regular components, i.e., monitor, CPU, keyboard and printer;

Central Counting Center

â a public place designated by the Commission where counting of ballots and canvassing shall be conducted;

Computerized Election System

â a system using electronic devices to count and canvass votes.

The Chairman of the Board of Election Inspectors or any authorized member thereof shall then retrieve the valid ballots from the ballot box. Under the supervision of the Election Officer of the municipality, the Chairman of the Board or any authorized member thereof shall feed the ballots one at a time into the machine without interruption until all the votes are counted. All proceedings shall be public; however, only the Election Officer authorized to operate the machine and the members of the Board of Election Inspectors of the precinct the ballots of which are being counted may physically touch the ballots.

After the ballots of the precincts have been counted, the Chairman of the Board of Election Inspectors or any member thereof shall, in the presence of the watchers, publicly read and announce the total number of votes obtained by each candidate based on the tape printout. The Election Officer shall print four (4) copies of the results all of which shall be authenticated by him and the members of the Board of Election Inspectors. The tape printout shall be distributed as follows:

The first copy to the Election Officer;

The first copy to the Election Officer;

The second copy to the authorized representative of the majority party;

The third copy to the authorized representative of the dominant minority party; and

The fourth copy to be deposited inside the ballot box.

The ballots shall then be returned to the ballot box, which shall be locked, sealed and delivered to the municipal treasurer for safekeeping. The treasurer shall immediately provide the Election Officer and the Commission with a record of the serial numbers of the ballot boxes and the corresponding metal seals.
